Mind like the sky, riding the waves of an emotion, a love that radiates like the sun. These are all natural to us, and luckily we have practices to remind us in the moments we forget.

Unpacking meditation and mindfulness 🧘🏽‍♀️💖

What is meditation? And why is it beneficial? And what is mindfulness? 

I share some answers to these questions along with some traditional and scientific ways of approaching them. I hope this can offer some clarity and motivation for engaging with these transformational practices. 

Physical benefits:
•Induce relaxation response
•Lowered heart rate, blood pressure, muscle tension 
•Boost immune system
•Better sleep

Psychological benefits:
•Improved focus and memory
•Honing attention skills
•Clear decision making
•Resilience
•Increase in positive emotions 
•Lower levels of stress

Social benefits:
•Greater capacity for empathy, compassion, altruism- making it more likely for us to help other people
•Ability to take on the perspective of another person
•Fosters connection and a greater sense of satisfaction in our relationships

#meditation #mindfulness @alomoves @aloyoga

Coming through the other side of a hibernation that felt deeply needed, reflective, and humanizing. Mothering 2 small, amazing people is an ADVENTURE. 

It is an adventure in unconditional love, and recommitting to that love again and again through each moment of turbulence. 

It is an adventure inviting me into my most creative and spontaneous expressions of play. 

It is an adventure into the depths of my most stuck patterns, presenting opportunity after opportunity for them to be examined and held in the light of understanding and tenderness. 

It is an adventure in the most delicious giggles, hugs wrapped with tiny arms, and watching eyes of wonder with all the time in the world explore this wild place. 

It is an adventure of constant recalibration because things are endlessly changing. 

It is the ultimate adventure in letting go…

It feels good to be re-emerging in this gorgeous spring weather ☀️🌷

There are some incredibly special beings in this world who radiate a sense of safety, acceptance, warmth, and love. Being with them is like being able to exhale fully. 

These beings can be a source of inspiration for us to know that we too can develop these qualities that are alive within us. When we connect with these qualities, they can be felt by others, just as we’ve felt them ourselves. As we take the time to nourish our own hearts, we create a ripple effect that can impact others in profound and meaningful ways. 

I’m so excited to be releasing a new class on @alomoves every week this month in support of Mental Health Awareness Month! Today’s class is *Nourish Your Heart* 

I’m looking forward to practicing together💞

A micro moment of calm and goodness to support the nervous system… 

I’ve been seeing the term glimmer show up recently, as in the opposite of a trigger. 

The term was coined by Deb Dana, a licensed clinical social worker who specializes in complex trauma. In her book "The Polyvagal Theory in Therapy," "glimmers" refers to small moments when our biology is in a place of connection or regulation, which cues our nervous system to feel safe or calm. 

Join me and my dear friend and meditation teacher @meganmook this evening at 7pm ET to nurture the nervous system with meditation, sound, and gentle breathing. Link in her bio! 🌸✨

Yes, we regularly see a couples counselor and it is so supportive for the health of our relationship. Relational health definitely doesn’t mean things are always smooth, easy, or in connection… what it has come to mean for us is that there’s room for each other. Room for our honesty, for our differences, for our vulnerability, for our strengths. There’s room to still be surprised by each other, room to mess up, room to repair, room to be human. 

I’m grateful to this human for being willing to dive into healing the histories we carry, and creating a life of meaning and discovery. 

It’s Mental Health Awareness Month, and this is one crucial element of my mental well-being. It feels important to normalize talking about our supportive resources because it actually does take a village, and that village can show up in so many ways. 

Big love to the relationships out there making room for each other ❤️

#mentalhealthawarenessmonth #relationalhealth #couplescounseling 

Headliner Tee @aloyoga

The more we practice anything, the more familiar we become with it. 💖

When we practice being present, we are meeting the fullness of each moment as it is… This is much easier said than done because we can often find ourselves wanting the moment to be different in some way… as we let go and open again and again, we have the opportunity to be with whatever is arising, whatever experience we’re having, just as it is…

When we can bring ourselves fully to each moment, we come to know our experiences intimately. There’s a deep sense of peace that can arise when we’re able to be with whatever is here, with a mind that is open and relaxed.

Let’s practice together. 💞 

New class *Nourish Your Presence* on @alomoves | @aloyoga

#mentalhealthawarenessmonth #meditation #presence #practice

As a teacher of mindfulness and meditation coupled with being a mother to 2 little ones, one question I am asked often is, “How can I get my kids to be more mindful?” 

My answer is pretty consistent: Establish a mindfulness practice of your own. 

As parents it is natural that we would want the best for our children, and with all the research supporting the benefits of mindfulness, it is no wonder this practice makes the list. My hope is that thinking about it as a practice frees us up from the idea that this is something we have to “get right,” and gives us permission to learn more about ourselves, think about the things that really matter to us, and how we’d like to engage with our kids, our family, and beyond.

How do you practice mindfulness with your kids? I’d love to hear your ideas!

To see a peacock fan it’s feathers is a pretty spectacular moment to witness. 🦚

Did you know peacocks possess the ability to consume what may seem poisonous, and transform those toxins into a kaleidoscope of vibrant colors? 
	
This incredible display of nature’s beauty became an opening for our family to talk about the way we can turn the challenges we face into opportunities to learn and grow. Poison, if approached skillfully, can become medicine. 
	
Fresh air, marvelous creatures, enriching conversations… we’re loving our time in CA ☀️🌿

I gave my mom a fresh cut this morning. I think she looks fabulous. 🙌🏼💖

This resilient little cookie keeps dancing through the ups and downs that cancer brings, and as hard as the challenges are, they reveal again and again how absolutely precious life is. 

There is a distinct moment from when she was in the hospital last month that I will remember with my whole body. It wasn’t anything big, it was a simple exchange. It was a moment when our conversation paused, and we were just looking at each other, fully alive and fully being in each other’s presence. She was smiling with her eyes and everything within me and around us seemed to be filled with love. Tears ran down my cheeks at how absolutely beautifully heart-opening and heart-breaking that moment was. To simultaneously know the limitation of our time together, and also embrace the fullness of life in that moment. 

This is a small glimpse of the gifts that are right under our nose all the time. May we be attuned to this preciousness and appreciate all that is here, right now. 💞✨🥰

Leaving this beautiful piece of wisdom right here for anyone that may benefit. 

For more context, it’s from @mingyurrinpoche’s wonderful book In Love with the World, and this quote though seemingly simple, holds so much depth. The preceding lines are: 
“Feeling divided from ourselves and the world around us is the deceptive narrative of the grasping mind. But we can learn to let go of false hopes that leave us yearning for ease in our bodies and in this world. We can move beyond our discontent. We can replace longing with love.”

Replace longing with love and see everything transform right in front of you. 😍

Full quote by Thich Nhat Hanh from The Miracle of Mindfulness ❤️💫

“Be yourself. Life is precious as it is. All the elements for your happiness are already here. There is no need to run, strive, search, or struggle. Just be. Just being in the moment in this place is the deepest practice of meditation. Most people cannot believe that just walking as though you have nowhere to go is enough. They think that striving and competing are normal and necessary. Try practicing aimlessness for just five minutes, and you will see how happy you are during those five minutes.”

Words cannot capture how much I will miss this extraordinary being who filled my life with the most generous kind of love I’ve ever known. He was our chosen family, a best friend, father-figure, mentor, teacher, spiritual companion… he was everything for me and my family. To my kids he was Uncle Perch. My friendship with him is one of the most meaningful and beautiful relationships I have ever known. I love this person so deeply, and his passing continues to take my breath away. He is alive in me in so many ways, and I am in complete gratitude for the many life lessons I learned just by watching him and being in his presence. Remembering him will always take my breath away, he was the most exquisite person I’ve had the honor of knowing. May his beautiful qualities live on through the many lives he touched. You are everywhere, dear Perch. I love you 💖🌈✨

Awareness is always with us. It has the ability to notice anything we are experiencing. Awareness can notice overwhelm, without being overwhelmed. It can notice impatience, without being impatient. Take some time to see how being in touch with awareness has the potential to shift your experience of an emotion. It won’t necessarily make it go away, but it has the ability to hold it with spaciousness, and allow it to pass.

*Calm and Steady* now on @alomoves

In these challenging times, many of us are navigating a whirlwind of emotions stirred by the world's heartache. In my morning classes, we’ve been having discussions  around staying committed to our inner work so that our outward engagement can be a skillful expression of that.

As we support ourselves and heal inward, we develop our capacity to be a source of support and healing in the world. I’m really grateful for moments to slow down and remember that love is alive in every one of us, and we have the ability to remind each other of it.

Things that feel nurturing for me during times that feel especially ungrounding:
- Holding my heart with a great deal of tenderness
-Connecting with others in intentional ways
-Feeling my seat pressing down into the earth beneath me

I’ll be sharing more practice opportunities in the coming days and weeks as a support for meeting our experiences with bravery and wholeheartedness. ❤️🌍

The value of retreat 💖

Spending time on retreat is an opportunity to deepen our practice and get know ourselves more deeply. To honestly get to know your own mind, your habits, your perceptions, the array of emotions and experiences that arise, and all the ways we react to them. 

It’s also catching a glimpse of what’s present beyond all that activity. To touch in and really get to know the most fundamental and beautiful aspects of you, and knowing *that* part of yourself more deeply. 

It’s basically a massive sigh of relief. 

To know that somewhere in our experience, we’re actually ok. 

What if we could relate to ourselves and each other from this place? 

Spending this kind of intentional time feels so meaningful right now. This is why my friends and Dharma teachers @megan.mook, Kate Greer Dickson (who just joined our teaching team!!), and I are offering this time away together in March – just after winter, when we all need the warmth and reconnection most. 

Let’s get to know ourselves more deeply on retreat in Costa Rica. 

Registration is open until Nov 1!

Sometimes when we hear the instruction to bring our attention to the breath in meditation practice, it can feel tight and rigid. By bringing a light touch of awareness to our breath, we can allow ourselves to simply be with the experience of breathing. 

Notice how natural it is for the body to breathe. This is something that happens all day and all night, and usually we aren’t aware of the fact that breathing is happening. Can you simply be aware of and connected to the fact that you’re breathing? Can you feel how your body and breath are in a kind of dance together? Our breath is always there for us, and can be a support to being aware of whatever experience we’re having. 

We can practice this anytime, no matter what we’re doing…
